rq2

How do the contributions of women key developers compare to the contributions of men key developers

To answer RQ2, we use the following datasets.

  • f_commits_ds: contains information about female contributions in terms of commits
  • m_commits_s1_ds: contains information about the first sample of male contributions in terms of commits
  • m_commits_s2_ds: contains information about the second sample of male contributions in terms of commits
  • m_commits_s3_ds: contains information about the third sample of male contributions in terms of commits
f_commits_ds <- read.csv("../datasets/commits_female_categorized.csv", head=T, sep=";")

Summarizing our dataset

commits_by_user <- sqldf("select login, gender, genderGroup,
                                 count(distinct hash_commit) commits,
                                 max(commit_date) max_date, 
                                 min(commit_date) min_date, 
                                 count(distinct commit_date) frequency, 
                                 sum(num_files) files ,
                                 sum(num_files_changed) files_changed,
                                 sum(num_files_deleted) files_deleted,
                                 sum(num_files_added) files_added,
                                 sum(num_files_renamed) files_renamed,
                                 sum(num_lines_changed) lines_changed,
                                 sum(num_lines_deleted) lines_deleted,
                                 sum(num_lines_added) lines_added
                          from commits_ds
                          group by login, gender, genderGroup")
                          

colnames(commits_by_user)
##  [1] "login"         "gender"        "genderGroup"   "commits"      
##  [5] "max_date"      "min_date"      "frequency"     "files"        
##  [9] "files_changed" "files_deleted" "files_added"   "files_renamed"
## [13] "lines_changed" "lines_deleted" "lines_added"
nrow(commits_by_user)
## [1] 146
bwplot(commits_by_user$commits~commits_by_user$genderGroup, ylab="Total number of contributions (commits)", par.settings = list(
                               axis.text = list(cex = 0.75),
                               par.xlab.text = list(cex = 0.75),
                               par.ylab.text = list(cex = 0.75)
                          ))

wilcox.test(commits_by_user$commits~commits_by_user$gender)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  commits_by_user$commits by commits_by_user$gender
## W = 1575, p-value = 0.06627
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
commits_by_user["date_diff"] = as.numeric(difftime(as.Date(commits_by_user$max_date), as.Date(commits_by_user$min_date), units="days"))
commits_by_user["frequency2"] = 100*commits_by_user$frequency / commits_by_user$date_diff 

cor.test(commits_by_user$frequency2, commits_by_user$commits, method="spearman")
## Warning in cor.test.default(commits_by_user$frequency2,
## commits_by_user$commits, : Cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  commits_by_user$frequency2 and commits_by_user$commits
## S = 449348, p-value = 0.1078
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.1336455
bwplot(commits_by_user$frequency2~commits_by_user$genderGroup, ylab="Frequency of commits", par.settings = list(
                               axis.text = list(cex = 0.75),
                               par.xlab.text = list(cex = 0.75),
                               par.ylab.text = list(cex = 0.75)
                          ))

wilcox.test(commits_by_user$frequency2~commits_by_user$gender)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  commits_by_user$frequency2 by commits_by_user$gender
## W = 1543, p-value = 0.4853
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
summary(commits_by_user[commits_by_user$gender == 'female',]$frequency2)

##  0.3264  1.1860  2.3479     Inf  6.2410     Inf

Size of the contribution

  • considering lines of code
lines <- commits_by_user[,c("login", "gender", "genderGroup", "lines_added", "lines_changed", "lines_deleted")]

lines <- melt(lines, id.vars = c("login", "gender", "genderGroup"))

lines <- lines[order(lines$variable),]

lines$variable <- gsub("lines_added", "Lines Added", lines$variable)
lines$variable <- gsub("lines_changed", "Lines Changed", lines$variable)
lines$variable <- gsub("lines_deleted", "Lines Deleted", lines$variable)


bwplot(log(value)~genderGroup|variable, data=lines,ylab="Lines of Code (log scale)",layout=c(3,1), par.settings = list(
                               axis.text = list(cex = 0.55),
                               par.xlab.text = list(cex = 0.75),
                               par.ylab.text = list(cex = 0.75)
                          ), par.strip.text = list(cex = 0.65))

ld <- lines[lines$variable == "Lines Deleted", ]
head(ld)

contributions_ds <- sqldf("select login, gender, genderGroup, class, count(*) total
                           from commits_ds 
                           group by login, gender, genderGroup, class")


bwplot(log(total)~genderGroup|class, data=contributions_ds, par.strip.text=list(cex=0.75),layout=c(5,1))

chisq.test(commits_ds$class, commits_ds$gender)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  commits_ds$class and commits_ds$gender
## X-squared = 766.92, df = 4, p-value < 2.2e-16

There is a huge difference in the number of commits. Perhaps we should first balance the dataset.

m_commits_s1_ds <- m_commits_s1_ds[sample(nrow(m_commits_s1_ds), 22326, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL),]

m_commits_s2_ds <- m_commits_s2_ds[sample(nrow(m_commits_s2_ds), 22326, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL),]

m_commits_s3_ds <- m_commits_s3_ds[sample(nrow(m_commits_s3_ds), 22326, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL),]

nrow(f_commits_ds)
## [1] 22326
nrow(m_commits_s1_ds)
## [1] 22326
nrow(m_commits_s2_ds)
## [1] 22326
nrow(m_commits_s3_ds)
## [1] 22326
commits_ds <- rbind(f_commits_ds, m_commits_s1_ds)
commits_ds <- rbind(commits_ds, m_commits_s2_ds)
commits_ds <- rbind(commits_ds, m_commits_s3_ds)

contributions_ds <- sqldf("select login, gender, genderGroup, class, count(*) total
                           from commits_ds 
                           group by login, gender, genderGroup, class")


bwplot(log(total)~genderGroup|class, data=contributions_ds,  par.settings = list(
                               axis.text = list(cex = 0.55),
                               par.xlab.text = list(cex = 0.75),
                               par.ylab.text = list(cex = 0.75)
                          ),  par.strip.text = list(cex = 0.65), layout=c(5,1))

chisq.test(commits_ds$class, commits_ds$gender)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  commits_ds$class and commits_ds$gender
## X-squared = 1069.1, df = 4, p-value < 2.2e-16
